{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17513304","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17513304"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:07:59+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:07:59+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12084"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17583625","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17583625"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:21:57+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:21:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12084"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12084","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12084"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.58,0.33,0.03,0.02,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4637"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78591"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4637","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4637"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12084"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63933"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"42"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"1109"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"1198"},{"type":"tags","id":"1750"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"3527"},{"type":"tags","id":"3549"},{"type":"tags","id":"4847"},{"type":"tags","id":"4945"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11631"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7039"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8556"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26779"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42705"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43883"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78591","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78591"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 38-year-old man is being reviewed after the finding of hypercalcaemia picked during a routine medical screening for insurance purposes. He has noted some fatigue, malaise, and a 2 kg weight loss over the last two months. He also has noted constipation and heartburn. He is occasionally nauseated after large meals and has water brash and a sour taste in his mouth. The patient denies vomiting, dysphagia, or odynophagia. He also notes decreased libido and depressed mood. The physical examination is unremarkable. His laboratory studies show:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECalcium 2.8 mmol/L (2.10-2.60)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPhosphate 1.04 mmol/L (0.8 to 1.5)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMagnesium 1.8 mmol/L (0.85 to 1.10)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlbumin 42 g/L (36-47)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETotal protein 70 g/L (6.4-83)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETSH 3.2 mIU/L (0.5\u20135.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EProlactin 250 \u03bcg/L (\u0026lt;425)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETestosterone 21 nmol/L(10.4-30.1)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESerum insulin-like growth factor 1 (IGF-1) 26 nmol/L (13-50)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESerum intact parathyroid hormone level 135\u00a0pg/mL (10-55)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGuaiac positive stool sample\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn abdominal computed tomography (CT) scan is performed, which shows a lesion measuring 2 \u00d7 2 cm in the head of the pancreas.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Multiple endocrine neoplasia (MEN) type 1","Multiple endocrine neoplasia (MEN) type 2","Multiple endocrine neoplasias (MEN) type 3","Polyglandular autoimmune syndrome","Von-Hippel Lindau (VHL) syndrome"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u2019s clinical condition is most consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003Emultiple endocrine neoplasia (MEN) type 1\u003C/strong\u003E, or the \u201c3 Ps\u201d: parathyroid, pituitary, and pancreas. MEN 1 is an autosomal dominant genetic syndrome characterized by neoplasia of the parathyroid, pituitary, and pancreatic islet cells. Clinical features most commonly include hyperparathyroidism and asymptomatic hypercalcaemia. MEN 1 is caused by an inactivating mutation of the gene that encodes the nuclear protein menin. The exact function of menin is unknown, but it appears to have tumor-suppressing effects. Two different forms, sporadic and familial, have been described. The sporadic form presents with two of the three principal MEN1-related endocrine tumors within a single patient, while the familial form consists of a MEN1 case with at least one first-degree relative showing one of the endocrine-characterising tumours.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPancreatic islet cell neoplasia is the second most common manifestation of MEN 1. Increased pancreatic islet cell hormones include pancreatic polypeptide, gastrin, insulin, vasoactive intestinal peptide, glucagons, and somatostatin. The symptoms depend on the type of hormone secreted. Pituitary tumours occur in up to half of the patients with MEN 1. Prolactinomas are the most common.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn \u003Cstrong\u003EMEN2, \u003C/strong\u003Ewhich is also called Sipple\u2019s syndrome and was previously referred to as MEN2a, medullary thyroid carcinoma (MTC) occurs in association with phaeochromocytoma and parathyroid tumors. In \u003Cstrong\u003EMEN3,\u003C/strong\u003E which was previously referred to as MEN2b, medullary thyroid carcinoma (MTC) and phaeochromocytoma occur in association with a marfanoid habitus, mucosal neuromas, medullated corneal fibers, and intestinal autonomic ganglion dysfunction leading to megacolon with the rare occurrence of parathyroid tumours. MTC may also occur as the sole manifestation of the MEN2 syndrome, and this variant is referred to as MTC-only.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPolyglandular autoimmune syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is characterized by autoimmune destruction of multiple endocrine glands, leading to conditions such as Addison\u0027s disease, type 1 diabetes, and autoimmune thyroid disease. It does not typically present with the combination of hyperparathyroidism, pituitary, and pancreatic tumors seen in MEN1.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVon-Hippel Lindau (VHL) syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is a genetic disorder characterized by the development of multiple tumors and cysts in different parts of the body, including hemangioblastomas, renal cell carcinoma, and pheochromocytomas. It does not typically involve the parathyroid, pituitary, or pancreatic islet cell tumors seen in MEN1.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Multiple endocrine neoplasias (MEN1) is a rare inherited multi-tumor syndrome, affecting specific neuroendocrine organs and non-endocrine tissues with a variable spectrum of over 20 possible different combinations, caused by inactivating heterozygote mutations of the MEN1 gene.","MEN1 is characterized by the presence of tumors in the parathyroid glands, pituitary gland, and pancreatic islet cells, often leading to hyperparathyroidism, pituitary adenomas, and pancreatic neuroendocrine tumors."],"references":["Marini F, Falchetti A, Del Monte F, Carbonell Sala S, Gozzini A, Luzi E, Brandi ML. Multiple endocrine neoplasia type 1. Orphanet J Rare Dis. 2006 Oct 2;1:38. doi: 10.1186/1750-1172-1-38. PMID: 17014705; PMCID: PMC1594566. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/17014705/","McDonnell JE, Gild ML, Clifton-Bligh RJ, Robinson BG. Multiple endocrine neoplasia: an update. Intern Med J. 2019 Aug;49(8):954-961. doi: 10.1111/imj.14394. PMID: 31387156. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31387156/","Falchetti A, Marini F, Luzi E, Giusti F, Cavalli L, Cavalli T, Brandi ML. Multiple endocrine neoplasia type 1 (MEN1): not only inherited endocrine tumors. Genet Med. 2009 Dec;11(12):825-35. doi: 10.1097/GIM.0b013e3181be5c97. PMID: 19904212. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/19904212/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63933"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12084"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63933","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63933"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-11T18:00:51+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-11T18:01:51+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4637"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78591"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83